com.jnape.palatable.lambda.adt.choice

Class Choice3<A,B,C>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.jnape.palatable.lambda.adt.choice.Choice3<A,B,C>
  • Type Parameters:
    A - a type parameter representing the first possible type of this choice
    B - a type parameter representing the second possible type of this choice
    C - a type parameter representing the third possible type of this choice
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    CoProduct3<A,B,C,Choice3<A,B,C>>, Applicative<C,Choice3<A,B,?>>, Bifunctor<B,C,Choice3<A,?,?>>, Functor<C,Choice3<A,B,?>>, Traversable<C,Choice3<A,B,?>>

    public abstract class Choice3<A,B,C>
extends Object
implements CoProduct3<A,B,C,Choice3<A,B,C>>, Applicative<C,Choice3<A,B,?>>, Bifunctor<B,C,Choice3<A,?,?>>, Traversable<C,Choice3<A,B,?>>
    Canonical ADT representation of CoProduct3 that is also a Functor and Bifunctor.

      • converge

        public final Choice2<A,B> converge(Function<? super C,? extends CoProduct2<A,B,?>> convergenceFn)
        Description copied from interface: CoProduct3
        Converge this coproduct down to a lower order coproduct by mapping the last possible type into an earlier possible type. This is the categorical dual of CoProduct2.diverge(), which introduces the type C and raises the order from 2 to 3.

        The following laws hold for any two coproducts of single order difference:

        • Cancellation: coProductN.diverge().converge(CoProductN::a) == coProductN
        Specified by:
        converge in interface CoProduct3<A,B,C,Choice3<A,B,C>>
        Parameters:
        convergenceFn - function from last possible type to earlier type
        Returns:
        a coproduct of the initial types without the terminal type
